WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:09.440 --> 00:00:14.440
- I started the lecture last
Thursday by playing a clip

00:00:14.930 --> 00:00:19.930
of Michael Foot making fun of
Sir Keith Joseph who had been

00:00:21.470 --> 00:00:25.382
the intellectual architect of Thatcherism.

00:00:25.382 --> 00:00:29.490
With his conjurer's trick,

00:00:29.490 --> 00:00:32.020
and said at the end of the day

00:00:32.020 --> 00:00:34.900
that the joke was on Michael Foot,

00:00:34.900 --> 00:00:39.900
because he thought Thatcher
would be a flash in the pan,

00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:45.200
and she went on to be Prime
Minister for 11 1/2 years

00:00:45.430 --> 00:00:48.530
and went on fundamentally to restructure

00:00:48.530 --> 00:00:53.378
the British economy and
political landscape as we saw.

00:00:53.378 --> 00:00:58.093
I want to start today
with a clip from his,

00:01:01.114 --> 00:01:04.330
his comrade in arms Tony Benn,

00:01:04.330 --> 00:01:08.760
who had been his staunchest
supporter on the left

00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:13.620
of the Labor Party throughout the 1980s.

00:01:13.620 --> 00:01:16.820
And actually ran for the deputy leadership

00:01:16.820 --> 00:01:21.290
when Michael Foot became leader In 1981

00:01:21.290 --> 00:01:25.440
and lost narrowly to Healy.

00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:30.440
But this is Tony Benn on
the day after Thatcher

00:01:31.859 --> 00:01:33.830
has announced she was stepping down,

00:01:33.830 --> 00:01:36.703
evaluating the Thatcher legacy.

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:39.797
- [Tony] Despite the fact we've been

00:01:39.797 --> 00:01:42.140
told we're an entrepreneurial society,

00:01:42.140 --> 00:01:43.550
this is a country today that

00:01:43.550 --> 00:01:47.060
has an utter contempt for skill.

00:01:47.060 --> 00:01:49.490
You talk to people who dig coal,

00:01:49.490 --> 00:01:54.150
run trains, doctors, nurses,
dentists, toolmakers,

00:01:54.150 --> 00:01:57.270
nobody in Britain is interested in them.

00:01:57.270 --> 00:02:01.080
The whole of the so-called
entrepreneurial society

00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:04.920
has focused on the city news
we get in every bulletin

00:02:04.920 --> 00:02:07.860
telling us what's happened
to the pound sterling

00:02:07.860 --> 00:02:10.050
to three points of decimals against

00:02:10.050 --> 00:02:12.140
a basket of European currency.

00:02:12.140 --> 00:02:14.470
Skill is what built this country,

00:02:14.470 --> 00:02:17.290
strength and it is treated with contempt.

00:02:17.290 --> 00:02:21.050
I must confess the auctioning
off of public assets,

00:02:21.050 --> 00:02:22.350
particularly the latest

00:02:22.350 --> 00:02:24.780
disgusting Frankenstein advertisements

00:02:24.780 --> 00:02:27.860
which told me more about the
mentality of the Minister

00:02:27.860 --> 00:02:31.660
who devised the scheme than
it did about the sale itself,

00:02:31.660 --> 00:02:34.330
these are assets built up by the labor

00:02:34.330 --> 00:02:36.590
of those who worked in electricity

00:02:36.590 --> 00:02:39.830
and by the taxpayer who
put the equipment in,

00:02:39.830 --> 00:02:42.240
now to be auctioned
off at half their price

00:02:42.240 --> 00:02:45.000
to make a profit from
the tax cut for the rich

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:47.290
before the next election comes.

00:02:47.290 --> 00:02:49.100
If these were local councilors

00:02:49.100 --> 00:02:52.770
they would be before the
courts for wilful misconduct,

00:02:52.770 --> 00:02:54.350
and because they are ministers

00:02:54.350 --> 00:02:56.785
and then some of them later go on

00:02:56.785 --> 00:02:58.800
the boards of the
company's they privatized,

00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:00.740
they are treated as businessmen

00:03:00.740 --> 00:03:02.750
who know better how to handle it

00:03:02.750 --> 00:03:04.630
as members of the board of directors

00:03:04.630 --> 00:03:07.250
than allegedly they did
as ministers responsible.

00:03:07.250 --> 00:03:08.790
The undermining of the trade unions

00:03:08.790 --> 00:03:09.990
with less rights in Britain

00:03:09.990 --> 00:03:12.790
than they have in Eastern Europe.

00:03:12.790 --> 00:03:16.010
The tax cuts for the rich and
benefit cuts for the poor,

00:03:16.010 --> 00:03:18.330
the censorship of the media,

00:03:18.330 --> 00:03:20.740
the abuse by security services

00:03:20.740 --> 00:03:23.940
the restriction of civil liberties.

00:03:23.940 --> 00:03:27.280
And when we look back in the 1980s

00:03:27.280 --> 00:03:30.170
we will see many victims of market forces.

00:03:30.170 --> 00:03:31.782
I do not share the general view

00:03:31.782 --> 00:03:35.530
that market forces are the
basis for political liberty,

00:03:35.530 --> 00:03:38.950
every time I see a person
in a cardboard box in London

00:03:38.950 --> 00:03:42.890
I say that person is a
victim of market forces.

00:03:42.890 --> 00:03:45.630
Every time I see a
pensioner who can't manage

00:03:45.630 --> 00:03:47.960
a victim of market forces.

00:03:47.960 --> 00:03:50.650
The sick who are waiting
for medical treatment

00:03:50.650 --> 00:03:54.240
that they could accelerate
by private insurance,

00:03:54.240 --> 00:03:57.300
they are the victims of market forces.

00:03:57.300 --> 00:03:59.866
And with the disappearance
of the Prime Minister

00:03:59.866 --> 00:04:02.120
who's a great ideologue,

00:04:02.120 --> 00:04:03.570
I mean her strength was

00:04:03.570 --> 00:04:06.940
that she understood a
certain view of life,

00:04:06.940 --> 00:04:09.490
and when she goes, and she's gone,

00:04:09.490 --> 00:04:11.733
there will be a great ideological vacuum.

00:04:12.978 --> 00:04:14.190
It's no good saying we will run

00:04:14.190 --> 00:04:15.940
the market forces better than she did,

00:04:15.940 --> 00:04:18.400
because her whole philosophy was

00:04:18.400 --> 00:04:20.740
that you measured the price of everything

00:04:20.740 --> 00:04:22.243
and the value of nothing.

00:04:23.080 --> 00:04:26.310
And I had one experience the other day

00:04:26.310 --> 00:04:28.070
which confirmed me in my view

00:04:28.070 --> 00:04:30.530
that she hasn't really changed

00:04:30.530 --> 00:04:32.530
the thinking or culture
of the British people.

00:04:32.530 --> 00:04:34.990
I don't know how many people
as I do travel on trains,

00:04:34.990 --> 00:04:36.570
but I go regularly on the trains

00:04:36.570 --> 00:04:38.611
and I see all the little businessmen

00:04:38.611 --> 00:04:41.300
with their calculators
working out their cash flow

00:04:41.300 --> 00:04:42.800
frowning at people,

00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:44.630
looking and glaring at each other.

00:04:44.630 --> 00:04:45.950
Thatcherite trains,

00:04:45.950 --> 00:04:47.920
the train of the competitive society.

00:04:47.920 --> 00:04:48.990
Coming back from Chesterfield

00:04:48.990 --> 00:04:50.763
the other day the train broke down

00:04:50.763 --> 00:04:54.370
and it wholly changed, somebody came in

00:04:54.370 --> 00:04:57.030
and said have a cup of
tea from my Thermos.

00:04:57.030 --> 00:04:59.550
Then people looked after
each other's children

00:04:59.550 --> 00:05:00.920
and a young couple talked to me

00:05:00.920 --> 00:05:02.197
and I said after about half an hour,

00:05:02.197 --> 00:05:03.197
"How long have you been married?"

00:05:03.197 --> 00:05:04.920
"We met on the train", they said.

00:05:04.920 --> 00:05:06.617
And a woman said, "Will
you get off at Derby

00:05:06.617 --> 00:05:09.170
"and ring my son in Swansea
because he'll be worried."

00:05:09.170 --> 00:05:12.510
By the time we got to London
we were a socialist train.

00:05:12.510 --> 00:05:17.470
Because you can't change human nature.

00:05:17.470 --> 00:05:19.280
There is good and bad in everybody,

00:05:19.280 --> 00:05:21.800
and for 10 years it is the bad.

00:05:21.800 --> 00:05:24.860
And the good that has
been denounced as lunatic,

00:05:24.860 --> 00:05:28.460
out of touch, cloud cuckoo
land, extremist and militant.

00:05:28.460 --> 00:05:31.180
And that's what the
party opposite have done,

00:05:31.180 --> 00:05:33.500
they don't quite yet know,

00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:36.910
they think it's the retirement
of a popular headmistress

00:05:36.910 --> 00:05:39.490
under circumstances some might regret.

00:05:39.490 --> 00:05:43.670
Actually, they killed the
source of their own philosophy

00:05:43.670 --> 00:05:47.033
and opened the way for
quite different ideas.

00:05:48.700 --> 00:05:53.700
- So there you have again a
leader of the Labor Party,

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:55.590
deputy leader of the Labor Party

00:05:55.590 --> 00:05:58.350
who's extremely eloquent,

00:05:58.350 --> 00:06:01.950
but in contrast to Foot a decade earlier,

00:06:01.950 --> 00:06:05.970
very bitter about the
legacy of Thatcherism.

00:06:05.970 --> 00:06:09.200
And more important for our purposes today,

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:10.950
despite his story about

00:06:10.950 --> 00:06:13.590
the socialist train and human nature,

00:06:13.590 --> 00:06:15.920
he was actually in denial,

00:06:15.920 --> 00:06:20.920
because Michael Foot and Tony
Benn continued to believe

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:24.436
that this ghastly interregnum was now over

00:06:24.436 --> 00:06:27.460
and there would be a resurgence of

00:06:27.460 --> 00:06:31.830
the traditional left, a
traditional Labor Party.

00:06:31.830 --> 00:06:34.240
By then of course Labor had been in

00:06:34.240 --> 00:06:36.550
the wilderness since 1979

00:06:37.990 --> 00:06:41.150
and it would actually continue
to be in the wilderness

00:06:41.150 --> 00:06:43.130
for the next several elections

00:06:43.130 --> 00:06:46.880
and not come back into power until 1997.

00:06:48.610 --> 00:06:50.740
And when they did finally come back into

00:06:50.740 --> 00:06:53.280
the power it was under the leadership of

00:06:53.280 --> 00:06:55.560
a very different Prime Minister

00:06:55.560 --> 00:06:58.510
with very different
priorities and views about

00:06:58.510 --> 00:07:01.693
the nature of the Labor Party
and how it could govern.

00:07:03.290 --> 00:07:06.270
- Across the nation, across class,

00:07:06.270 --> 00:07:09.090
across political
boundaries the Labor Party

00:07:09.090 --> 00:07:13.650
is once again able to represent
all the British people.

00:07:13.650 --> 00:07:17.760
We are the mainstream
voice in politics today.

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:20.830
A believe in society, working together,

00:07:20.830 --> 00:07:24.550
solidarity, cooperation, partnership.

00:07:24.550 --> 00:07:28.800
These are our words, this is my socialism.

00:07:28.800 --> 00:07:30.640
(audience applauds)

00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:33.830
It's not the socialism
of Marx or state control,

00:07:33.830 --> 00:07:37.580
it is rooted in a
straightforward view of society.

00:07:37.580 --> 00:07:40.760
In the understanding that
the individual does best

00:07:40.760 --> 00:07:42.900
in a strong and decent community

00:07:42.900 --> 00:07:45.060
of people with principles

00:07:45.060 --> 00:07:48.960
and standards and common aims and values.

00:07:48.960 --> 00:07:50.470
A new politics,

00:07:50.470 --> 00:07:54.753
a politics of courage
and honesty and trust.

00:07:56.310 --> 00:07:58.073
Now it means telling it as it is,

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:00.550
it means not opposing everything

00:08:00.550 --> 00:08:02.960
every other party does for the sake of it.

00:08:02.960 --> 00:08:06.933
Politicians are looked to by
the people for leadership,

00:08:08.160 --> 00:08:09.720
and leadership is about having

00:08:09.720 --> 00:08:12.973
the courage to say no as well as yes.

00:08:14.040 --> 00:08:15.447
Now even this week I heard people say

00:08:15.447 --> 00:08:17.950
that a Labor government must repeal all

00:08:17.950 --> 00:08:20.000
the Tory trade union laws.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.810
Now there's not a single
person in this country

00:08:22.810 --> 00:08:25.940
who believes that we shall actually do it,

00:08:25.940 --> 00:08:28.670
no one believes strike
balance should be abandoned.

00:08:28.670 --> 00:08:29.680
So why do we say it?

00:08:29.680 --> 00:08:31.731
We shouldn't, and I won't.

00:08:31.731 --> 00:08:33.060
I have said and I mean I am committed

00:08:33.060 --> 00:08:34.850
to the goal of full employment

00:08:34.850 --> 00:08:37.014
we will develop the plans to achieve it.

00:08:37.014 --> 00:08:41.420
But I won't ever pretend that
I can deliver it overnight.

00:08:41.420 --> 00:08:43.630
It requires a modern constitution,

00:08:43.630 --> 00:08:45.567
that says what we are in terms

00:08:45.567 --> 00:08:47.545
the public cannot misunderstand

00:08:47.545 --> 00:08:49.424
and the Tories cannot misrepresent.

00:08:49.424 --> 00:08:50.480
(audience applauds)

00:08:50.480 --> 00:08:52.010
The next election will offer us

00:08:52.010 --> 00:08:54.240
the chance to change our country.

00:08:54.240 --> 00:08:57.660
Not just to promise
change, but to achieve it,

00:08:57.660 --> 00:09:00.570
the historic goal of
another Labor government,

00:09:00.570 --> 00:09:02.570
our party New Labour,

00:09:02.570 --> 00:09:04.410
our mission new Britain,

00:09:04.410 --> 00:09:06.202
New Labour, new Britain.

00:09:06.202 --> 00:09:09.202
(audience applauds)

00:09:13.670 --> 00:09:15.950
- So that was Tony Blair speaking

00:09:15.950 --> 00:09:20.580
to the Labor Party Conference in 1995.

00:09:20.580 --> 00:09:23.110
And the reason that was
such an important speech,

00:09:23.110 --> 00:09:26.033
once that was the speech in which,

00:09:27.230 --> 00:09:28.230
when he speaks about

00:09:28.230 --> 00:09:30.240
the new Constitution for the Labor Party,

00:09:30.240 --> 00:09:33.260
he's talking about
getting rid of clause four

00:09:33.260 --> 00:09:35.670
of the Labor Party's Constitution

00:09:35.670 --> 00:09:37.040
which called for

00:09:37.040 --> 00:09:40.070
the nationalization of
the means of production,

00:09:40.070 --> 00:09:42.130
distribution and exchange,

00:09:42.130 --> 00:09:44.766
and it hearkened back to
the original founding of

00:09:44.766 --> 00:09:49.020
the Labor Party in the early
part of the 20th century

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:52.100
as a Marxist Socialist party.

00:09:52.100 --> 00:09:55.460
And there had been a battle
for the soul of the Labor Party

00:09:55.460 --> 00:10:00.453
that had gone on since Thatcher's years,

00:10:01.980 --> 00:10:05.560
actually it was before
Blair, it was Neil Kinnock,

00:10:05.560 --> 00:10:07.980
and after Kinnock it was John Smith,

00:10:07.980 --> 00:10:10.200
but Blair finally won this battle,

00:10:10.200 --> 00:10:11.930
he got rid of clause four

00:10:11.930 --> 00:10:15.332
and reoriented the Labor Party to become

00:10:15.332 --> 00:10:19.310
a party that they thought
could be competitive in

00:10:19.310 --> 00:10:24.310
the new world that I was
describing to you last time.

00:10:24.480 --> 00:10:27.540
Now similar things were
going on elsewhere,

00:10:27.540 --> 00:10:29.540
including back here.

00:10:29.540 --> 00:10:32.050
The Democrats felt that
they had been pulled to

00:10:32.050 --> 00:10:36.455
the left too much in the decade since

00:10:36.455 --> 00:10:40.590
the McGovern Frazier reforms
of the Democratic Party

00:10:40.590 --> 00:10:43.270
which had greatly
empowered the grass roots.

00:10:43.270 --> 00:10:46.150
I'll talk more about that later,

00:10:46.150 --> 00:10:49.513
and had produced candlelight
dates like George McGovern

00:10:49.513 --> 00:10:51.830
or subjected Jimmy Carter

00:10:51.830 --> 00:10:56.830
to a debilitating primary
challenge from Jimmy Carter

00:10:56.970 --> 00:10:58.600
which many thought had contributed

00:10:58.600 --> 00:11:03.060
to his defeat by Ronald Reagan in 1980.

00:11:03.060 --> 00:11:06.990
And there was a similar
sense within the Labor Party,

00:11:06.990 --> 00:11:10.260
within the Democrats that just
as something like New Labour

00:11:10.260 --> 00:11:15.040
which Tony Blair was
bringing into existence

00:11:15.040 --> 00:11:20.040
needed to happen in the US as
well to the Democratic Party,

00:11:20.120 --> 00:11:21.810
and there was something formed called

00:11:21.810 --> 00:11:24.991
the Democratic Leadership
Council and Bill Clinton

00:11:24.991 --> 00:11:29.991
was one of its first leaders.

00:11:30.270 --> 00:11:33.840
And the agenda of the
Democratic leadership Council

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:37.950
was very much similar to
the agenda of New Labour,

00:11:37.950 --> 00:11:39.730
just to give you a flavor,

00:11:39.730 --> 00:11:44.730
this is Bill Clinton
actually speaking in 1988,

00:11:45.420 --> 00:11:48.893
before he ran for the
nomination four years later.

00:11:50.020 --> 00:11:52.800
- Take this fight about civil rights,

00:11:52.800 --> 00:11:55.770
the Republicans have set
up so that if you're for

00:11:55.770 --> 00:11:58.860
the civil rights bill
you've got to be for quotas,

00:11:58.860 --> 00:12:00.310
so that if you're not for quotas

00:12:00.310 --> 00:12:03.220
we have to say you're for discrimination.

00:12:03.220 --> 00:12:05.350
It's a bogus debate,

00:12:05.350 --> 00:12:08.250
and the White House ought
to be ashamed of itself

00:12:08.250 --> 00:12:10.349
for breaking up the honest.

00:12:10.349 --> 00:12:13.349
(audience applauds)

00:12:15.930 --> 00:12:18.390
For breaking up the honest attempt of

00:12:18.390 --> 00:12:19.550
the Business Roundtable

00:12:19.550 --> 00:12:21.470
and the civil rights
groups in this country

00:12:21.470 --> 00:12:24.540
to have a new choice you
can have economic growth,

00:12:24.540 --> 00:12:26.050
small-business vitality,

00:12:26.050 --> 00:12:27.700
you don't wake up every day being scared

00:12:27.700 --> 00:12:28.770
to death of a lawsuit,

00:12:28.770 --> 00:12:31.210
but we protect women and minorities

00:12:31.210 --> 00:12:32.450
and people who deserve it

00:12:32.450 --> 00:12:34.220
from unfair discrimination on the job,

00:12:34.220 --> 00:12:36.453
which we all know still
exists in this country.

00:12:36.453 --> 00:12:39.453
(audience applauds)

00:12:42.280 --> 00:12:45.083
Take the debate about poor children,

00:12:46.440 --> 00:12:48.150
the way the Republican's
set the debate up,

00:12:48.150 --> 00:12:49.410
they say the Democrats

00:12:49.410 --> 00:12:51.640
are for throwing more
money at these problems

00:12:51.640 --> 00:12:54.370
and we know you can't throw money at them.

00:12:54.370 --> 00:12:56.480
We just said that.

00:12:56.480 --> 00:12:58.880
And we are family values.

00:12:58.880 --> 00:13:00.180
Let me tell you something,

00:13:01.210 --> 00:13:04.563
family values won't feed a hungry child,

00:13:05.560 --> 00:13:06.440
but you can't raise

00:13:06.440 --> 00:13:09.173
that hungry child very well without them.

00:13:10.020 --> 00:13:12.840
We need both.

00:13:12.840 --> 00:13:15.410
Do you really believe that if we permit

00:13:15.410 --> 00:13:19.050
these conditions to go
on for 10, 20 or 30 years

00:13:19.050 --> 00:13:21.610
And we permit national
politics to continue in

00:13:21.610 --> 00:13:25.000
its present relevant track
for 10 or 20 or 30 years,

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:26.960
that America will lead
the world we have made,

00:13:26.960 --> 00:13:28.905
that you can keep the American dream alive

00:13:28.905 --> 00:13:31.680
for the next generation of Americans?

00:13:31.680 --> 00:13:34.700
I want my child to grow
up in the America I did,

00:13:34.700 --> 00:13:37.600
I don't want her to be part
of the first generation

00:13:37.600 --> 00:13:40.090
of Americans to do worse
than their parents did.

00:13:40.090 --> 00:13:41.720
I don't want her to be
a part of the country

00:13:41.720 --> 00:13:44.070
that's coming apart
instead of coming together.

00:13:45.460 --> 00:13:48.760
Over 25 years ago I had a professor

00:13:48.760 --> 00:13:51.610
of Western civilization
who told me our country was

00:13:51.610 --> 00:13:53.290
the greatest country in human history

00:13:53.290 --> 00:13:58.090
because our people had always
believed in two simple things,

00:13:58.090 --> 00:14:01.230
one is that the present doesn't have

00:14:01.230 --> 00:14:02.370
to be as good as the future,

00:14:02.370 --> 00:14:04.610
the future can always be better.

00:14:04.610 --> 00:14:07.720
And two, that every one of us has

00:14:07.720 --> 00:14:12.720
a personal moral
responsibility to make it so.

00:14:12.850 --> 00:14:16.100
That is what the new choice is all about,

